wackpackr.util

Class CircularDoublyLinkedList<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • wackpackr.util.CircularDoublyLinkedList<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the class of elements stored in a list instance

    public class CircularDoublyLinkedList<E>
extends Object
    Limited application of a circular, doubly linked list with a sentinel node. Offers only a few basic operations, nowhere near as extensive as e.g. the List interface.

    Elements are always added to the end of the list, and hence ordered "chronologically" from the oldest to the most recently added element. Duplicate and null elements are permitted.

    Performance presumably is what can be expected from a linked list with zero optimisation. In other words, this is not a smart choice for anything, unless using a linked list in particular can be justified.

    Author:
    Juho Juurinen

      • toArray

        public Object[] toArray()
        Returns all elements in this list as an array in proper sequence: that is, in the order they were added to the list.

        There are no references between the list elements and the returned array, so the caller can safely modify the array without fear of undesired side-effects.

        Returns:
        an array containing all list elements from first to last

      • toArrayReverse

        public Object[] toArrayReverse()
        Returns all elements in this list as an array, ordered from the last element on the list to the first: that is, from the most recently added to the oldest one.

        There are no references between the list elements and the returned array, so the caller can safely modify the array without fear of undesired side-effects.

        Returns:
        an array containing all list elements from last to first
